<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-03-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="247" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d247">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 5315/813.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Bacon</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase—Extract.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-03-02"><hi rend="italic">March 2,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Mr. Bacon states that the foreign office has not yet received a reply
                            from England, but in answer to his specific question said that he might
                            inform his Government that France would be perfectly <pb facs="0386" n="274" xml:id="pg_274"/> satisfied to accept proposition to concede
                            to France 100 kilometers Ch’eng-tu extension, England to satisfy them as
                            to subengineer Hankow-Canton, France to have westernmost division of
                            Ch’eng-tu extension.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>